The issue isn't so much the worldbuilding itself but how it's utilized.
>notably of her home region of New Caen, which, like most of Hathia outside of the main city, is sparsely settled and even more sparsely visited
You have details like this in the prose that don't really matter and are just kind of mentioned in passing. Stuff like this can be implied in how the characters act, maybe you could have played up Jenny's countryside mannerisms.
Sometimes it feels like the characters are just reciting facts instead of really responding to what each other are saying. There was a good part where the word "Furbloods" gets a reaction out of Jenny but it feels like it could have been a lot stronger. It sounds like it would have some kind of derogatory connotation.
There was another weird moment where Anon gets excited about Little Gascony, but it doesn't go anywhere. It would have been a nice place to add both worldbuilding and backstory simultaneously.
>"Closer to Le Babord, but close enough." She is clearly excited that you actually know a bit about the region given how a slight yip is let out at the end
could be
>"Le Babord, actually!" she yips. "I think it's really cool that you know about the area. Have you ever been?"
Writing the line this way gives Anon an in to talk about his own experiences, and allows you to describe that area without having to dive too deep into exposition. It also expresses Jenny's excitement without stating it outright.

The more characters involved, the less time you have to build up each individual relationship. Even just from a writing perspective this is true; you'll have to choose what portion of the words go to which characters, and even though you can double or triple up by having several to a scene, you can only stretch it so far before it gets lost and things become purely physical. Not that that's bad for a horny fapfic, but it definitely makes it harder to write emotional things.
One solution to this is to have a definite "main girl" for romance and the others on the team being occasional hookups, but this leaves a bad taste in my mouth and implies a lot of things about the characters attitudes towards relationships that can hollow things out.
